	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Efforts underway to improve Kenyan rice production </h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 December 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, new rice production methods are to be introduced in Kenya which use ‘up to 50% less water’ while improving ‘yields, grain quality size and aroma’. Kenya consumes an estimated 300,000 tonnes of rice annually, with consumption growing at an estimated 12% per annum.</p><p>One of the disadvantages of the new techniques is that ‘it requires more weeding, since weeds tend to grow more rapidly under un-flooded conditions’. However this is compensated for by the higher yields. By July 2011, ‘more than 1,800 farmers had been trained on the new system in the Mwea rice scheme’.</p><p>New varieties of seed better suited to local conditions are also being developed. The combination of improved rice varieties and better production techniques are expected to ‘meet the supply deficit for local consumption and provide surplus for exports’.</p><p>This forms part of wider efforts to boost rice production in the EAC in the face of surging demand and heightened rice price volatility.</p><p>According to analysis in a leading rice trade publication, ‘rice prices may rise to $700 per ton next year’. Global rice production is currently being adversely affected by flooding in Cambodia, Vietnam (although exports are still set to rise almost 3%), and most severely in Thailand. The Thai government’s rice purchase policy is also likely to drive up prices, as are purchases by other major rice-consuming nations (e.g. Philippines and Indonesia). The likely return of India to the rice export trade is likely to only slightly ameliorate these price pressures.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Thecropsite.com</i>, ‘Farmers adopt new method to grow more rice with less water’, 26 September 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9227/farmers-adopt-new-method-to-grow-more-rice-with-less-water " target="_self">http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9227/farmers-adopt-new-method-to-grow-mo...</a></p><p><i>New Vision</i> ‘Renovation of Doho rice scheme starts’, 27 September 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201109281265.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201109281265.html</a></p><p><i>Thecropsite.com</i>, ‘Global rice prices may soar on demand’, 23 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9454/analysts-12-global-rice-prices-may-soar-on-demand" target="_self">http://www.thecropsite.com/news/9454/analysts-12-global-rice-prices-may-...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Changing dietary trends due to a number of factors (patterns of food aid and urbanisation effects) are boosting rice consumption, and gradually reducing consumption of traditional crops (sorghum and cassava) across the EAC. Specific constraints that have inhibited rice production in Kenya include high cost of inputs, poor extension, mismanagement of large-scale irrigation schemes, poor marketing, limited rice-milling capacities and poor producer prices. In Western Kenya, efforts to promote rain-fed rice production, for example, were undermined by a lack of milling facilities.</p><p>For a long time, rice marketing was heavily controlled by the state through the National Cereals and Produce Board, which was mandated (among other things) to purchase and store national strategic grain reserves. Rice production on the other hand was coordinated by the National Irrigation Board, which still manages key public irrigation schemes such as Mwea, Ahero and Bunyala, with farmers mainly providing labour. There has been little private sector involvement to date in rice development.</p><p>However, technical improvements to methods of rice production form only one part of the challenge in stimulating rice production in Kenya. Experience elsewhere in the ACP suggests that the quality of rice produced is important in order to ensure consumer acceptance of expanding domestic rice production. This appears to be equally the case in Kenya, where consumers are very particular about rice quality and variety. Establishing appropriate standards for the production, milling and packing of rice therefore constitute important government priorities, in the evolving regional context.</p><p>Elsewhere, careful attention is being paid to strengthening the functioning of the rice supply chain by rebalancing the power relationship between farmers and millers, to ensure that rice farmers are quickly paid for their rice and are able to benefit from rising international rice prices (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Rice/Guyana-s-rice-exporters-urged-not-to-neglect-traditional-markets" target="_blank">Guyana’s rice exporters urged not to neglect traditional markets</a>’, 23 November 2011). This would appear to be an important consideration under any moves to strengthen the role of the private sector in the rice sector development.</p><p>At the regional level, trade in rice, like other staple food crops, is not entirely liberalised, within both the EAC and the wider COMESA framework. Import or export bans are common, especially during perceived food shortages, despite the EAC’s work in developing quality standards for grains in order to facilitate trade. This hinders both efforts to promote a regional approach to food security through fostering regional trade, and also the development of private sector rice trading networks.<i>&nbsp;</i></p>
		</div>
		
